-- South African Stocks: Anglo Platinum, Mr Price, Simmer and Woolworths
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-11-22T17:18:12Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-22/anglo-american-bhp-billiton-lead-gains-in-south-african-equities-trading.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  was little changed, advancing 4.99, or less than 0.1
percent, to 31,403.81 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo Platinum Ltd.  (AMS SJ), the world’s biggest producer
of the metal, snapped two days of gains, weakening 8 rand, or
1.2 percent to 690 rand. Platinum declined 0.7 percent to $1,652
an ounce.  Dorbyl Ltd.  (DLV SJ), a mechanical engineering company,
declined to hit a 20-year low, losing 8 cents, or 2.6 percent,
to 2.99 rand, the weakest since August 1990. The company had a
loss of 475,000 rand ($68,000) for the six months through
September, according to a filing with the exchange after the
market closed on Nov. 19.  Mr Price Group Ltd.  (MPC SJ), a clothing and furniture
retailer, rose for the second day in three trading days,
advancing 46 cents, or 0.7 percent, to 64.30 rand. The stock was
raised to “buy” from “sell” by Citigroup Inc.  Simmer & Jack Mines Ltd . (SIM SJ), a gold producer, gained
the most since Nov. 11, climbing 4 cents, or 4.4 percent, to 95
cents. The company posted cash operating profit of 7.9 million
rand in the three months through Sept. 30 from a loss of 52.8
million rand during the previous quarter. It expects the
Buffelsfontein mine to produce 21,000 ounces in the current
quarter and Tau Lekoa some 30,000 ounces.  Woolworths Holdings Ltd.  (WHL SJ), a clothing and food
retailer, fell for the fourth consecutive trading day, losing 39
cents, or 1.4 percent, to 27.31 rand, the lowest since Oct. 28.
The stock was downgraded to “hold” from “buy” by Citigroup.  To contact the reporter on this story:
